## Appendix B Derivation of uncertainty formulae

Consider the following quantities with their actual uncertainty:

\[R_{1}=A\pm\Delta A\quad\text{ and }\quad R_{2}=B\pm\Delta B\]

**(a) Addition**

Let \(W=R_{1}+R_{2}\).

maximum \(W=(A+\Delta A)+(B+\Delta B)=(A+B)+(\Delta A+\Delta B)\)

minimum \(W=(A-\Delta A)+(B-\Delta B)=(A+B)-(\Delta A+\Delta B)\)

\(\Delta W=\gamma_{2}\) (maximum \(W-\) minimum \(W\)) \(=\Delta A+\Delta B\)

Hence, \(W\pm\Delta W=(A+B)\pm(\Delta A+\Delta B)\)

**(b) Subtraction**

Let \(X=R_{1}-R_{2}\).

maximum \(X=(A+\Delta A)-(B-\Delta B)=(A-B)+(\Delta A+\Delta B)\)

minimum \(X=(A-\Delta A)-(B+\Delta B)=(A-B)-(\Delta A+\Delta B)\)

\(\Delta X=\gamma_{2}\) (maximum \(X-\) minimum \(X\)) \(=\Delta A+\Delta B\)

Hence, \(X\pm\Delta X=(A-B)\pm(\Delta A+\Delta B)\)

From **(a)** and **(b)**, we can see that when quantities are added and/or subtracted, the _actual uncertainty is the sum of the individual actual uncertainties_.

**(c) Multiplication**

Let \(Y=R_{1}\times R_{2}\).

maximum \(Y=(A+\Delta A)\times(B+\Delta B)=AB+B\Delta A+A\Delta B+\Delta A\Delta B\)

minimum \(Y=(A-\Delta A)\times(B-\Delta B)=AB-B\Delta A-A\Delta B+\Delta A\Delta B\)

\(\Delta Y=\gamma_{2}\) (maximum \(Y-\) minimum \(Y\)) \(=B\Delta A+A\Delta B\)

Hence, \(Y\pm\Delta Y=AB\pm(B\Delta A+A\Delta B)\).

But this is not an easy form to remember, especially in cases with more than 2 quantities in the equation. Instead, we divide the actual uncertainty, \(\Delta Y\), with \(Y\) throughout.

\[\frac{\Delta Y}{Y}=\frac{B\Delta A}{Y}+\frac{A\Delta B}{Y}\]

Since \(Y=AB\), we have

\[\frac{\Delta Y}{Y}=\frac{B\Delta A}{AB}+\frac{A\Delta B}{AB}\]

Hence, for multiplication of quantities, the _fractional uncertainty is given by the sum of the individual fractional uncertainties of the quantities_.

